Assignment 9: Visualization - Revealing a graph

How to do it?:

  • Open the Rmarkdown file of this assignment (link) in Rstudio.

  • Right under each question, insert a code chunk (you can use the hotkey Ctrl + Alt + I to add a code chunk) and code the solution for the question.

  • Knit the rmarkdown file (hotkey: Ctrl + Alt + K) to export an html.

  • Publish the html file to your Githiub Page.

Submission: Submit the link on Github of the assignment to Canvas

  1. Use the dataset by of covid 19 by WHO at https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv. Find the three countries with the most numbers of deaths by Covid-19.
library(tidyverse)
df <- read_csv('https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv')
df %>%
  filter(Date_reported == '2021-10-22') %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarise(average_deaths = mean(Cumulative_deaths)) %>% 
  arrange(-average_deaths)
## # A tibble: 237 x 2

Hint: - Use filter to select the most current date - Pipe with arrange(-Cumulative_deaths) to rank the data by the number of cumulative deaths

  1. Make a plot revealing the number of deaths in the three countries with the most numbers of deaths
library(gganimate)
df %>% 
    filter(Country_code %in% c('US','IN','BR')) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(y=Cumulative_deaths,
               x=Date_reported,
               color=Country_code))+ 
    geom_line()+
    geom_point(size=3)+
    geom_text(aes(label = Cumulative_deaths), 
              hjust = -.1, size=5) +
    transition_reveal(Date_reported)

  1. Create the new variable (column) death_per_cases recording the number of deaths per cases (Hint: divide cumulative deaths by cumulative cases). What are the three countries with the highest deaths per cases?
library(tidyverse)
library(gganimate)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
df$death_per_cases <- df$Cumulative_deaths/df$Cumulative_cases

df %>%
  filter(Date_reported == '2021-10-22') %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarise(deaths_per_cases = mean(death_per_cases)) %>% 
  arrange(-deaths_per_cases)

  1. Make a plot revealing the number of deaths per cases of the US, Italy and Mexico.

  1. Use transition_reveal to create three animated graph with the vaccination data at
library(tidyverse)
df <- read_csv('https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv')
df %>% filter(Date_reported == '2021-10-22')
## # A tibble: 237 x 8
##    Date_reported Country_code Country             WHO_region New_cases Cumulative_cases
##    <date>        <chr>        <chr>               <chr>          <dbl>            <dbl>
##  1 2021-10-22    AF           Afghanistan         EMRO              32           155891
##  2 2021-10-22    AL           Albania             EURO             566           180029
##  3 2021-10-22    DZ           Algeria             AFRO              70           205599
##  4 2021-10-22    AS           American Samoa      WPRO               0                4
##  5 2021-10-22    AD           Andorra             EURO               0            15382
##  6 2021-10-22    AO           Angola              AFRO             227            63567
##  7 2021-10-22    AI           Anguilla            AMRO              45              743
##  8 2021-10-22    AG           Antigua and Barbuda AMRO              45             3984
##  9 2021-10-22    AR           Argentina           AMRO            1218          5275984
## 10 2021-10-22    AM           Armenia             EURO            2146           291052
## # ... with 227 more rows, and 2 more variables: New_deaths <dbl>,
## #   Cumulative_deaths <dbl>
library(lubridate)
library(gganimate)
d1 <- df %>% group_by(Date_reported, Country) %>% summarise(mean = mean(Cumulative_deaths, na.rm=TRUE))
d2 <- d1 %>% group_by(Date_reported) %>% mutate(rank=rank(-mean)) %>% ungroup()
d3 <- d2 %>% filter(rank <= 3)
a1 <- d3 %>% ggplot(aes(x=rank, y=mean, group=Country, fill=Country, label=Country))+
  geom_col()+
  geom_text(aes(y = mean, label = Country), hjust = 1.4)+ 
  coord_flip(clip = "off", expand = FALSE) +scale_x_reverse()+
  labs(title = 'Date_reported {closest_state}', x='', y='Cumulative_deaths', fill='Country')+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1, size = 22),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y  = element_blank(), legend.position = "none")+
  transition_states(Date_reported)+
  ease_aes("cubic-in-out")
animate(a1, nframes=400)

library(lubridate)
library(gganimate)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
df2 <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/govex/COVID-19/master/data_tables/vaccine_data/us_data/time_series/vaccine_data_us_timeline.csv')


d11 <- df2 %>% group_by(Vaccine_Type, Province_State) %>% summarise(mean = mean(Doses_admin, na.rm=TRUE))
d12 <- d11 %>% group_by(Province_State) %>% mutate(rank=rank(-mean)) %>% ungroup()
d13 <- d12 %>% filter(rank <= 3)
ab1 <- d13 %>% ggplot(aes(x=rank, y=mean, group=Province_State, fill=Province_State, label=Province_State))+
  geom_col()+

        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
